segments.text: The 16th, Monday morning, and I am visiting with Dr. Herman Brown, head of the Department of Agricultural Education.
Back to August, I mean November 16th at Scotes Hall.
Scotes Hall.
Scotes Hall Inn.
Texas A&M University, Dr. Herman Brown, head of the Department of Agricultural Education.
And we're going to talk a little bit about changes.
And you've been here since 19... 66.
You preceded the College of Education.
Yes.
And you were in the Department of?
agriculture education at the time.
Right.
See, I have not got this department straight in my head.
I know I've already visited a couple of people, and it's in the part in the education and part in the agriculture.
We have a dual appointment, College of Education, College of Agriculture.
Administratively, we're in the College of Agriculture, but nationally our ties with the College of Education as it relates to certification.
To certification, all right.
Primarily certification.
Again, there's other courtesies extended here in the employment of personnel and so forth.
Okay.

Now, tell me a little bit about A&M when you were here in 66 and some of the major changes as they relate more to the College of Education, because my dissertation is the history of the College of Education.
I know there's a little bit written up to 1967.
There was a Robey thesis that talked a little bit about what
happened before the college was initiated.
So can you take it from there for a little bit?
In 1966, we were Department of Education.
At that time, Dr. Frank Hubert was responsible for that.
He had other responsibilities in the College of Liberal Arts.
Naturally, in 1966, total enrollment at Texas A&M was possibly, I don't recall specifically, 7 or 8,000 students.
So we're certainly not talking about size magnitude then as we are now.

at that particular time we were just bringing in our first females we did not have a large department of education at that time our relationship really in ag education has not changed that much because we were still in agriculture but our ties were very strong with the college of education we serve as we do today on all of their committees unless it's an in-house
type of college committee.
At that time we served on the Council on Teacher Education just as we do now.

Certainly the numbers, I think the quality is not, certainly not what is demanded today because at that time the College of Education was no different than any other segment of the university as far as grade point requirements or any other standardized test.
Yes, I think we've come a long way since 1966 or the past 21 years from our perspective.
And other than the women and some of these, you know, the growth, is there anything that in the external environment that affected your department growth or your...
other than just the numbers growing?
Have there been changes in society or philosophical change?
Any kind of changes that have affected your department?
It seems as the university has increased in numbers, our numbers have steadily declined over the years.
We are more directly associated with agriculture than what we are education.
And as I put both of those together, agriculture and education, that's somewhat of a vulgar term.
It's not an in vogue term today among people.
Both of them have a negative connotation.
And so we have slipped in enrollment through the years.
We have managed to turn that around at this point in time.
But our numbers in the department are not today what they were in 1966 or 1970.
Give me just a couple of numbers just for ideas.
Say maybe what's your enrollment now versus what it might have been.
OK, our enrollment right now is approximately 160 undergraduate students.
And in 1970, it would be something like 225.
OK.
When you say negative connotations, do you mean that both things have negative connotations?
Well, yes, there's lots of things involved here.
Agriculture, first of all, the economy is down.
An oversupply, an overabundance of agricultural commodities.
We have an emphasis on the so-called higher education track system in our public schools, in which very few students are really encouraged to go into agriculture.
For example, if you have a 1200 SAT, school counselors are prone to recommend one of these so-called professions,
or what I refer to as a syndrome, my son the medical doctor, my daughter the lawyer.
Those professional things, I believe, have captured the eye and imagination of our counselors.
Counselors have a profound impact upon young people and where they go to school in their advisement.
So with that combination, I think that we've had to restructure our recruitment procedures for...
to maintain enrollment.
And you said you're turning that around right now.
Is there something special that you're doing?

We're working primarily with teachers of agricultural science in our public schools and the extension people, asking them just to provide us with one or two names of outstanding students in their school who might have an interest in agriculture.
at the senior, junior, sophomore, and freshman level.
We have selected about 150 teachers across the state.
They provide us with that information and then
What we do is we get on the telephone and call these people.
And say sometime at 6 o'clock in the afternoon, and that's when Mama is home fixing the evening meal, and we really don't want to talk to the student as much as we want to talk to Mama.
We recruit mothers, and if we can sell them on the idea that we will certainly look after the son or daughter while we've got a friend, then it makes recruitment much easier for us.
As the changes now in this case, it's reversed for you because most of them, the numbers have gotten so big that my question is how has it affected your working with students?
Does the numbers allow you to have more time then to work or interact with students or is it the same?
No, no difference from that perspective.
For the simple reason we have several service courses in this department.

So as the university increases its enrollment and the placement of the core curriculum, which includes some of our particular courses, then we've had to increase the number of service courses that we provide.
Which are the core curriculums?
For example, Agricultural Ed 440 Methods of Technological Change is one of the social science courses that's adopted.
Okay.
committee and we also have one 340, a youth leadership training program.
And I'd say in those two courses, 90% of the students are our total enrollment, non-AGET students.
In fact, in the teacher certification option, those two courses are not even required.
I'm asking this a lot in the College of Education, and I don't know how it pertains more to the agriculture, but the mission of the land grant is the teaching, the service, and the research.
How is that balanced in your department?
Do you emphasize one more than the other, or are they equal?
Well, certainly the teaching, research, and service is the part that you're talking about here.
We feel like we're strong in teaching.
We feel like that we're exceptionally strong in service activities, in working with people on a non-credit type basis.
We recognize the need for research, but that is by far our weakest area.
We have research going on, but funding becomes a major problem, and we are not a member of the Agricultural Experiment Station in the College of Agriculture, which funds the research.
And because most of our research is in the area of developmental research.
And that does not seem to be the major thrust of research today in the social sciences.
Okay, now collaboration, and obviously because you're in both departments
You have some collaboration with both.
Is there collaboration between your department and other areas to any great extent?
Well, as I put it out here, we're already outside for one thing.
So I look upon our collaboration with the College of Education just as much as any other college.
Certainly right now our inquiry group, we're a vital part of that.
So I'd say...
Well, Sylvia, we have an opportunity here.
We get to serve on twice as many committees as most other departments.
And so, you know, it's really reinforced.
Do you consider that a plus or a minus?
I consider it a plus.
Now, it does get time-consuming.
I think if we could spend some time on research instead of preparation for these meetings.
For example...
We have two department head meetings a month in the College of Education, whereas we only have one in the College of Agriculture.

So I find no problem with this for the simple reason that what one dean brings up in one way, then the other will bring it up in another way, then I feel like I can understand what is needed a little bit better.
So there's no problem there.
HOW ABOUT PERCEPTIONS OUTSIDE THE COLLEGE?
YOU KNOW, HOW IS THE COLLEGE?
WE TOUCHED A LITTLE BIT ABOUT IT AND ABOUT COUNSELOR'S PERCEPTIONS AND SO FORTH.
IS THERE ANYTHING ELSE?

I GET THE IDEA SINCE I SERVE ON A DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL, MEANING THAT THE DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL IN YOUR COLLEGE IS EXCEPTIONAL AND IS ABLE TO RAISE TONS OF MONEY BECAUSE EVERYBODY OUT THERE, YOU KNOW, IS VERY SUCCESSFUL AND HAS ALL KINDS OF MONEY.
WHEREAS FOR THE COLLEGE OF EDUCATION, WE HAVE HAD
very difficult time raising any amount of money whatsoever.
So how does that... Well, okay.
Now here, I don't want to get on the bandwagon a little bit, but this is one of the primary reasons that education is not a profession to begin with.
And until we become a profession, we are going to have that difficult time of raising money.
Now the medical doctors, one of the
One criteria for being a profession is that the profession supports its students with scholarships.
We see that in the medical profession.
We see that in engineering.
We see that in the law profession, the ministerial profession, all of those things.
So until we arrive at that point.
Now the other thing, true dedicated teachers don't have money.
I mean, gosh, after all,
They have a salary.
It's a full-time job.
You can't make your millions and fortunes just in the summertime.
So really, teaching is more of a dedicated group of people where the fiscal or financial rewards do not seem to be as paramount as it does with those involved in private business.
So I think we're just going to have to accept we will never be an elitist group
from that point of view.
Now, there may be some things that we need to do.
For example, the former Students Association here at A&M is stronger now than it was 20 years ago because of numbers.
The College of Education is still in its infancy, and I think in time to come, maybe 25 years down the road,
then yes, we will be able to attract some dollars.
But I don't see any way of doing it this time.
It's a losing cause.
OK, you just touched a little bit about the future and what the College of Education might be later on.
What about this upheaval in the whole new teacher training program and how everybody's going to be affected by that, or at least some departments?
Now, you have your students take, are there some that take education courses, or is it, how is the tie?
For example, an undergraduate student, do they take half of the courses here and half in the College of Education, or do they have to just take the number of courses to be certified?
OK. We have what we call vocational certification.
And really, don't ask me how to differentiate between secondary certification, vocational education.
I don't see that different.
Now, our students have a 48-hour program in agriculture, which is comparable to the two 24-hour teaching field.
In addition to that,

Currently, we have 24 hours of required professional education, and that has been very specifically identified as 12 hours of ag ed to include six hours of student teaching and 12 hours from the College of Education.
Now, we have followed that track for many, many years,
The Commission on Standards of the Texas Education Agency is the one that dictated the 12 and the 12.
So those changes, we just have to live with.
Are they going to affect you drastically?
I mean, if they change where you can only take, what, 18 hours of education, including teaching?
Then we will have 12 hours of ag ed and six hours of professional education.

we are in disagreement with some of the philosophy that's being espoused at this time as to a five-year program uh we contend that currently we don't really have a four-year program now we have a four and a half or five-year program and then you complicate this with a another year plus an internship year which we're talking about seven years
possibly, and then this qualifies an individual to start at very minimum wage.
Now, in this department, we're a little bit different than some of the others.
Most of the graduates of this department will be the breadwinner of the family.
This will not be a secondary income.
So at $15,000 to $18,000 a year after seven years of training,
will certainly be the kiss of death in many respects to this department as far as numbers are concerned.
Now, it is my understanding that we can have companion four-year programs and five-year programs.
So that decision, final decision, has not been made.
We know that there's some support on this campus for the philosophy of the Holmes group,
We understand that NCAID is revising their standards, which may have an impact on some of this.
But to be perfectly honest with you, the time may come when an attempt will be made by this department as a matter of survival to withdraw from NCAID accreditation.
Do you have a choice on that?
No, not really.
But at this point in time, we have two deans to satisfy.
And we have a dean of agriculture who says my departments must all be competitive at the same number of semester credit hours.
So he cannot afford to let one department have 130 hours for graduation and another one 155.
And these are going to cause some problems.
And then you throw in the core curriculum.
I think what we're seeing here at this point in time that is very frustrating to the professionals in this department is that we have two EA standards, which is mandated legislatively.
We have the Southern Association.
We have NCATE.
We have our own institutional core curriculum requirements.
Then we have a college requirements.
And then if the Holmes group comes in,
It just boils down to a matter of how many masters can be served.
So that pretty much answers my question on the future.
So right now it seems a little fussy.
There's certainly uncertainty.
Okay.
Now let's talk about Herman Brown and some of the highlights or some of the things that you have experienced.
I'm having the difficulty getting people to
express their contribution, they prefer somebody else to do it, but what do you feel the best about what's gone on since you've been here that you've impacted or influenced?
Well, first of all, I think I have served on every committee in the university, and many of them as chairman.
We're talking about faculty committees.
We're talking about elected committees to the university under the provost, under the president.
This is a continual thing as we continue to strive for maturity.
I think that
the greatest contribution maybe we as faculty members in this department, and specifically Herman Brown, to be honest with you, we are the only vocational unit at Texas A&M University.
We do not have home economics, we don't really have T&I, business administration, health education, and those types of things.
So I think that we have been able to add a flavor to programs, especially at the advanced degree level,
to provide administrators and potential administrators with a vocational philosophy that they might not get otherwise.
Give me the philosophy as you see it from this department or how it might differ from other ones in the College of Education, for example.
Some of them do not have it even, it's not expressed, it's just sort of understood, but is there a
philosophy as such from this department that you espouse?
Well, sure.
We have our own written goals and so forth, but what it boils down to is the compatibility of general education and vocational education.
And this is another concern that we have today.
Every youngster in high school, it'd be impossible for them to all go to
to college or higher education.
So we have some who cannot meet the entrance requirements.
We have some who really don't have an interest in higher education.
Now, what are these young people going to do?

So we say that general education has to be strong, but that vocational education has a place in the public schools for those who have an interest in a livelihood that requires training less than a college degree.
So what we're seeing here is that we feel like there's a need in the public schools to offer programs that train young people for entry-level world of work experiences.
It's sort of like my homespun philosophy of what is vocational education.
I jokingly tell folks at times, it is that training that helps keep people off the welfare road.
If young people have a skill, then they can be productively employed.
And I contend that everybody wants to be productively employed and not be on the welfare rolls or without employment or living on the family.
So really I see general education and vocational education being very compatible, going down the railroad track side by side,
If you push me which one is the most important, certainly I'm going to have to say general education.
In my own personal philosophy, there's not enough money to pay the salary of a good first grade teacher and a second grade.
That's where it all starts.
Personally, I have some philosophies with kindergarten, pre-kindergarten.
You know, I just think that there's a time when young people need to be
Babies, sometimes we don't let them be babies long enough.
I have a daughter who is a school teacher who gave me my third grandchild this past Friday afternoon.
And economic conditions, the way they are, as soon as she possibly can, she'll have to go back to the classroom.
So my grandson is going to have to be put under somebody else's care, against my wishes.
But that's the way the economic and social structure seems to work today.
Okay, what about any insights or observations or even an anecdote or so that might stand out in your mind over this long standing career that you lead?
Oh, I've had lots of good things to happen.
In this department, we take great pride in that
All of our people have received the Distinguished Service Award in Teaching by the Informal Students Association.
So these are some of the things that we strive for.
It's sort of a personal goal.
But to me, that indicates a level of excellence in teaching, especially when young people say, hey, you're good enough for this type of award.
Our young people, we have one faculty member who will be
In December, become the president of all the teacher educators in agriculture in the United States for 1987-88. Who is that?
That's Dr. Don Herring.
We have another young faculty member who is a member of the Young Astronaut Program in Agriculture, Dr. Joe Townsend.
And he spends time in Florida with that group and will be going down in December.
And that has to do with the coordination of science and agriculture in the space program.
We'd like to be on the cutting edge here.
Someday we will, agriculture will be as much of an outer space as it is here in this country.
Maybe not in our lifetime, but we're starting on that.
So we have lots of good things going for us along those lines.
There was a time when the pendulum was way over on the vocational and agriculture and all.
And then it keeps going back and forth, though, right?
I mean, right now, would you say it's swung the other direction by your comment about the negative attitude towards...
not only agriculture, but vocational in general, isn't it, with this parole thing?
Has that had a real, really great impact on Attitude?
Well, first of all, a lot of people
condemn Ross Perot for his involvement in the educational process.
I am not that critical of Ross Perot because we had changes in agriculture that needed to be made that we could not make for the simple reason we had a clientele of teachers who would not accept it.
So we needed somebody strong and forceful like Ross Perot to come in and mandate some changes.
Can you specify a couple of those changes?

Those changes in which we will do away with the traditional production one, two, three, and four of agriculture, of teaching shows and contests, of getting away from the production aspect of cows, plows, and sows, and get into some semester courses.
And this department and this faculty, on a faculty retreat about a year ago, we developed 23 semester-length courses that is being implemented across the state.
And due to the diversity of agriculture in the state, the teachers and the community can select courses that's applicable to them.
For example, the folks in the Rio Grande Valley, they've got a specialty type of agriculture in citrus that students in Amarillo just don't have a need to know.
Now, we're not talking about basics and fundamentals and principles.
But we have generally broken this into areas such as the horticultural sciences, the agribusiness, the ag mechanics, the environment, and these things can be applicable.
For example, I can see a need
in the Houston area for somebody to get involved in the raising of research animals.
Rats, guinea pigs, hamsters.
Hey, that's agriculture.
But that might not be true at SNCC.
For example, the only area where primate animals are raised is in San Antonio.
I'm not saying that we're going to get involved in raising monkeys and so forth as a big agricultural enterprise, but I think we have become so highly specialized
that we can no longer cover the waterfront in our teaching.
So that's a big change.
So House Bill 72 and 246, we've even been impacted by Senate Bill 994.
Now we're able to keep our name, agricultural education.
And we don't have to go the interdisciplinary route like some of the others.
We appeared two weeks ago before the advisory committee,

coordinating board in five minutes time we pleaded our case and look we've got 48 hours of agriculture we only have 24 going to 18 hours of education it takes 12 hours in your major to get a degree from an institution they said fine good you don't belong under this umbrella here of senate bill 994 which we feel good about so those are just some of the impacts and in closing do you have any words of wisdom

Well, I never did have much wisdom, but I think one of the biggest problems that we're running into, I think, at this time, in addition to all these things that we have discussed, the paperwork has become horrendous.
And I'm sure this is in all facets of society.
And so much of our work today is involved in what I have referred to here, that we are involved in too many non-teacher education functions.

And I think whenever that happens, this takes away from the close relationship and working and concentration on the improvement of the individual who will be going into the classroom at some point in time.
So I am hopeful that in the years to come that we can devote more time to working with the certification program.
try to better prepare young people for the classroom.
Again, we're at odds on some of these things.
We have one half semester of student teaching, or nine weeks.
And we have a number of folks who are advocating a whole year of student teaching.
And we have asked for research.
There is no research.
And we talk about research-based competencies.
There is no research.
That tells us that one full year or even one semester of student teaching is better than a half a semester.

Now, a concern that we really have in this department is that we've got the pre-student teaching work in the schools, we've got student teaching, and then we've got a year of, a proposed year of internship in those schools.

Now, it's well and good for us to be working with these individuals, but what about the poor student that's in school trying to get through the elementary and high school when he or she is subjected to student teachers or bombarded by student teachers or observers every day of the week?
I think that no one has really addressed this problem.
